[1. Following the announcement by the Danish prime minister of the total banning of mink farming nationally (20201105.7918210, 20201106.7922587, 20201109.7929573), the media published conflicting information about the timetable, even questioning its very application. Formal updated information about the said will be useful. Denmark's last update on COVID-19 in minks, notifying the general culling decision, was submitted to the OIE on 5 Nov 2020 (https://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/MM/Update_6_Letter_to_the_OIE_on_Sars-CoV-2_in_Denmark_5_november2020.pdf).

2. To follow and fulfill WHO's advice (measures 2, 3, and 4, above) pertaining to "surveillance for COVID-19 at the animal-human interface where susceptible animal reservoirs are identified, including on mink and other fur farms," as well as "sequencing of SARS-CoV-2 from animal samples" and "strengthen[ing] farming biosafety and biosecurity measures around known animal reservoirs, particularly on mink farms," enhanced efforts are required. The establishment, preferably by an international animal health institution, of an updated list of mink-farming countries, including information on their respective COVID-19 surveillance activities, is essential for such objectives. The absence of data from leading mink-farming countries such as China and Poland is of particular concern. - Mod.AS]

******
[2] Netherlands: approaching the termination of mink farming
Date: Mon 30 Nov 2020
Source: Nieuwe Oogst [in Dutch, trans., abridged, edited]
https://www.nieuweoogst.nl/nieuws/2020/11/30/op-nog-maar-vier-bedrijven-nertsen-aanwezig


Mink is currently present at only 4 farms. Agriculture minister Carola Schouten announced this to the House of Representatives on Monday [30 Nov 2020] evening during the debate about the early termination of fur farming.

It is expected that all animals, including the dams, will be culled in the course of next week. At that time there are no longer any minks present in the Dutch mink-farming sector. Minister Schouten said she was grateful that the mink farmers are cooperating in this and that all animals are pelted [comment].

Due to the corona outbreak, the minister wants the ban on fur farming to take effect 3 years earlier [than initially planned]. Originally, the ban was due to take effect on 1 Jan 2024. The minister wants to prevent mink farms from serving as a reservoir for the coronavirus and thus posing a risk to public health.

70 companies/farms were cleared at an earlier stage because the coronavirus was found on those companies [see footnote]. Mink farmers are entitled to compensation from the government because of the mandatory stopping earlier than planned.

It is possible that mink farmers will receive an advance on the compensation after the entry into force of the law.

[Byline: Martijn van Rossum]

