Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The birth period of minks in Europe normally takes place late April to mid-May. The kits are weaned when 8 weeks old. By the end of August, the physical development of the mink is more or less complete; continued weight gain consists primarily of fat. The selection of animals for the following year's breeding stock begins at the end of October. This is when the animals' size, behaviour, health, and pelt quality are evaluated. Animals not selected for breeding are pelted. The pelting season begins in November/December. During the pelting process, the skin is prepared in such a way that it can keep for up to a year without being dressed. The skins are placed on drying boards in order for them to maintain their shape during the drying process. The said timetable is presented as background to Minister Schouten's remark about the early completion of the current year's pelting.

Footnote:
An earlier posting, published 27 Nov 2020 (20201125.7972425), included item "[1] Netherlands: 70th outbreak, Gelderland." This was subject to a note from the Dutch Veterinary Services, which said: "There was not a 70th outbreak in the Netherlands in mink. The positive PCR that was found in the EW samples was not followed by a confirmation in the official samples taken by the Competent Authority. The animals have been culled precautionary because of a severe suspicion in a new region in the country." We are grateful for the correction of the said media-derived information. - Mod.AS

